  "instructions": "========================\nCORE PRINCIPLE\n========================\nEDR observability overrides completeness.\n\nExtract only relationships that:\n- Are explicitly stated in the text (\"X spawns Y\", \"X launches Y\", \"Y was executed by X\")\n- Identify a concrete parent process AND a concrete child process\n- Can realistically produce a process_creation detection (Sysmon Event ID 1, EDR process_creation)\n\nWhen uncertain -> EXCLUDE\nPrecision > Recall. Favor under-extraction.\n\n========================\nEXTRACTION SCOPE\n========================\nExtract explicit parent-child process execution chains such as:\n- Office applications spawning scripting hosts (winword.exe -> cmd.exe, excel.exe -> powershell.exe)\n- Services hosts spawning attacker binaries (services.exe -> malware.exe, svchost.exe -> evil.dll host)\n- LOLBins spawning shells or payloads (rundll32.exe -> cmd.exe, regsvr32.exe -> powershell.exe)\n- Scripting hosts spawning binaries (powershell.exe -> rundll32.exe, wscript.exe -> malware.exe)\n- Boot persistence chains (wininit.exe -> services.exe -> attacker-controlled service)\n- Any explicit ancestor-descendant pair the article calls out\n\n========================\nGLOBAL OUTPUT RULES\n========================\n1) Output ONLY valid JSON.\n2) No explanations, reasoning, markdown, comments, or extra text.\n3) JSON MUST be parseable by json.loads().\n4) Response MUST start with { and end with }.\n5) Escape Windows backslashes for JSON (each \\ becomes \\\\).\n6) Do NOT wrap the JSON in triple backticks or any fenced code block.\n\n========================\nREQUIRED OUTPUT SCHEMA\n========================\n{\n  \"process_lineage\": [\n    {\n      \"value\": \"string (canonical form: '<parent> -> <child>')\",\n      \"parent\": \"string (parent process image name, e.g., services.exe)\",\n      \"child\": \"string (child process image name, e.g., malware.exe)\",\n      \"arguments\": \"string or null (child command-line arguments, verbatim, if stated)\",\n      \"source_evidence\": \"string (verbatim paragraph from the article describing this spawn relationship)\",\n      \"extraction_justification\": \"string (which prompt rule triggered this extraction)\",\n      \"confidence_score\": \"number 0.0-1.0\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"count\": integer\n}\n\nCONFIDENCE SCORE CALIBRATION (guidance, not a stored field):\n  0.9+     = parent and child are named explicitly AND the article uses an explicit spawn verb (spawns, launches, executes, calls, starts, creates process)\n  0.6-0.89 = parent and child are named but the spawn relationship is implied by common malware behavior patterns in the article\n  0.3-0.59 = ambiguous phrasing but both endpoints are named\n\nIf no valid lineage relationships are found, output EXACTLY:\n{\"process_lineage\":[],\"count\":0}\n\n========================\nDEFINITION: VALID LINEAGE RELATIONSHIP\n========================\nA relationship is valid ONLY if ALL conditions are met:\n\nA) EXPLICIT SPAWN VERB\n- The article uses language such as: spawns, launches, executes, starts, calls, invokes, creates process, child process of, parent of.\n- Co-occurrence of two process names in the same paragraph is NOT sufficient.\n\nB) CONCRETE ENDPOINTS\n- Both parent and child are named as specific Windows images (*.exe, *.dll via rundll32, signed binaries) or recognizable process names.\n- Generic references like \"a child process\" or \"the payload\" without an image name are INVALID.\n\nC) SINGLE-HOP PAIRS\n- Extract one edge per item. For a three-generation chain (A -> B -> C), emit TWO items: {parent: A, child: B} and {parent: B, child: C}.\n- Do NOT collapse multi-hop chains into a single item.\n\nD) DETECTION RELEVANCE\n- Both endpoints must be observable in Sysmon Event ID 1 / EDR process_creation telemetry.\n\n========================\nFIELD RULES\n========================\n- value: canonical string of the form '<parent> -> <child>' (spaces, arrow, spaces). Use this exact format for deduplication purposes.\n- parent: just the image name (e.g., 'services.exe'), not a full path unless the article only provides a full path.\n- child: same rule as parent.\n- arguments: the child's command-line arguments verbatim if the article states them; null otherwise. Do NOT reconstruct or infer arguments.\n- source_evidence: The verbatim sentence or paragraph from the article that describes this spawn relationship. No paraphrasing.\n- extraction_justification: Short description of which prompt rule or pattern triggered this extraction (e.g., \"Office-to-shell lineage with explicit spawn verb\", \"Service host launching attacker binary\").\n- confidence_score: numeric 0.0-1.0 aligned to the calibration guide above.\n\n========================\nITEM RULES\n========================\n- Each unique (parent + child + arguments) = ONE item.\n- Same (parent, child) mentioned multiple times with consistent arguments = ONE entry.\n- Same (parent, child) with differing arguments = SEPARATE entries.\n- Do NOT merge partial relationships across unrelated sentences.\n\n========================\nHARD EXCLUSIONS (DO NOT EXTRACT)\n========================\n- Single processes with no explicit parent or child in the text.\n- Generic statements (\"malware runs commands\", \"persistence is established\") without named endpoints.\n- Hypothetical examples (\"e.g., an attacker could use winword.exe to spawn cmd.exe\").\n- Inferred relationships based on malware family knowledge rather than article text.\n- Non-Windows process relationships.\n- API function call traces without corresponding process_creation observables.\n- Co-mentioned process names in the same paragraph when no spawn relationship is stated.\n\n========================\nFINAL VALIDATION (MANDATORY)\n========================\nBefore outputting:\n- Verify each item has both a concrete parent image name and a concrete child image name.\n- Verify each item references an explicit spawn verb in source_evidence.\n- Verify arguments is null when the article does not state child arguments.\n- Verify source_evidence is present and verbatim for every item.\n- Verify extraction_justification is populated for every item.\n- Verify confidence_score is numeric and within 0.0-1.0.\n- Verify value is the canonical '<parent> -> <child>' form.\n- Verify count equals len(process_lineage).\n- Verify no exclusions apply.\n- If ANY doubt exists, EXCLUDE the item.\n\nOutput ONLY the JSON object."
